Several independent implementations of Mailchimp Model Context Protocol (MCP) servers exist, providing varying levels of API coverage for tasks like audience management, campaign creation, and reporting [1][2][3]. These servers facilitate communication between AI clients and the Mailchimp Marketing API v3 [2][4][3].

To configure a server, you typically add a block to your MCP client configuration file (such as `claude_desktop_config.json`) specifying the command and environment variables, including your API key [1][4].

Example configuration:
```json
{
  "mcpServers": {
    "mailchimp": {
      "command": "uvx",
      "args": ["mailchimp-mcp"],
      "env": {
        "MAILCHIMP_API_KEY": "your-key-us8"
      }
    }
  }
}
```

Options range from comprehensive servers with over 270 tools [2][3] to more specialized versions [5]. Features may include read-only modes, dry-run capabilities, and audit logging for security [1][6].
